  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Memorial Requesting Retirement
  author: Kim Bu-sik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The day wanes and the road stretches far—surely it is time to stay one's steps. Heaven stands high yet listens to those below, and surely fulfills their desires. I dare lay bare my sincere heart, humbly beseeching your majesty.

    I rose from humble origins and undeservedly entered great office. Day and night alike, in all my comings and goings, I have accomplished nothing—my talents are meager, my abilities short. My remaining years grow thin, my strength insufficient; how can I sustain myself? Moreover, the Classics speak of retiring from office, and the Way teaches the virtue of knowing when enough is enough. Those who cling to fortune without departing must surely perish like fish that snap at the bait.

    Therefore I should gather this weary frame and clear the path for worthier men. I humbly beseech your infinite benevolence and boundless wisdom: grant mercy to this aging creature. As the tired bird seeks its nest to rest, as the wandering fish seeks its home—allow me too to find my proper place.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This is a formal petition (pyo/표) submitted to the king, a standard genre in classical Korean administrative literature. The elaborate parallel structures and elaborate courtesy formulas reflect the highly codified nature of such official documents.
  - key: ''
    value: The references to 'weary bird' and 'wandering fish' draw on classical Chinese literary imagery to represent retirement and finding one's natural place, common metaphors in both Daoist and Confucian philosophical discourse.
